```

Pattern:
- Single exported function matching command name (camelCase)
- Imports from core modules
- Returns array of strings (lines to print)
- No console.log; all output goes through return value

**Example 2: Command with Arguments (add-product.js)**

```javascript
'use strict';

const { AppError } = require('../lib/errors.js');

const added = [];

function addProduct(args) {
  const [id, name, priceStr] = args;
  if (!id || !name || !priceStr) {
    throw new AppError('usage: add-product <id> <name> <price>', 2);
  }
  const price = parseFloat(priceStr);
  if (isNaN(price)) {
    throw new AppError('price must be a number', 2);
  }
  added.push({ id, name, price });
  return [`added product ${id}`];
}

module.exports = { addProduct };
```

Pattern:
- Receives args array (positional arguments)
- Validates with AppError (exit code 2 for usage/validation errors)
- Modular state management (added array)
- Returns result lines
- Exit code conventions: 1 = default error, 2 = usage/validation error

**Example 3: Command Registry (registry.js)**

```javascript
'use strict';

const { listProducts } = require('./list-products.js');
const { listOrders } = require('./list-orders.js');
const { listCustomers } = require('./list-customers.js');
const { addProduct } = require('./add-product.js');
